removal_notes:
Complete removal of plate and revision of plating surgery.
Patient moved back to Edmonton and hardware was removed by Dr Joseph Bergman because of 'Painful orthopaedic hardware'. The plate and was broken with the medial screws all loose hardware. The fracture was then provisionally stabilized, and an appropriately sized and contoured titanium clavicle-specific plate was selected. The medial and lateral fragments were then secured to the plate, and locking screws were then used to stabilize the construct.   Final fluoroscopic images were then obtained, showing a satisfactory reduction and hardware placement.
 
The wound was then closed in layers beginning with the periosteum. The platysma was then closed using 2-0 Vicryl again and taking care to continue to protect the supraclavicular nerve. Skin was then closed with 2-0 Vicryl deep dermal and 4-0 Monocryl subcuticular layers. Adhesive and absorbent dressings were then applied, and the patient was placed in a sling for comfort.
comp_reop_notes:
surgery for Painful orthopaedic hardware 
The previous plate and screws were identified and exposed.  The plate appeared to be a modular hand plate and was broken with the medial screws all loose.  The sum total of the screws and plate segments were sent for instrument culture.  6 samples of tissue were also sent for culture.
The fracture was then provisionally stabilized, and an appropriately sized and contoured titanium clavicle-specific plate was selected. The wound was then closed in layers beginning with the periosteum. The platysma was then closed using 2-0 Vicryl again and taking care to continue to protect the supraclavicular nerve.
